    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-10-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-10-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="328"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d328">
                <head>328. Message From President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1" type="from"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> to Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_ERHSA1"
                        type="to">Eden</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d328fn1">Source: <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName> Library, Whitman File, <persName
                            corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>–Herter Series. Top Secret. A”
                        Suggested Draft”, attached to the source text, is presumably the one handed
                        by <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> to <persName
                            corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> during their conversation that
                        morning (see <ref target="#d327">
                            <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>
                        </ref>); it bears a few stylistic changes by <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName>. The revised draft, which <persName
                            corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> initialed, corresponds to the
                        text sent to <persName corresp="#p_ERHSA1">Eden</persName>, except for the
                        P.S. which was presumably added by the President shortly before
                        transmission. The message was transmitted for immediate delivery to
                            <persName corresp="#p_ERHSA1">Eden</persName> in telegram 2628 to
                        London, October 11, 7:02 p.m. (Department of State, Central Files,
                        974.7301/10–1156)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-10-11">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 11, 1956</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear <persName corresp="#p_ERHSA1">Anthony</persName>
                    </hi>: Let me acknowledge the note from you<note n="2" xml:id="d328fn2">
                        <ref target="#d287">Document 287</ref>.</note> which transmitted a copy of
                        <persName corresp="#p_BNA1">Bulganin</persName>’s letter to you. Truly, this
                    is a rather forbidding letter, and it is scarcely couched in the terms which one
                    would expect in a communication from one Head of Government to another. Also,
                        <persName corresp="#p_FAB1">Foster</persName> tells me that <persName
                        corresp="#p_SDT1">Shepilov</persName> made a quite nasty speech at the
                    United Nations Council last Monday.</p>
                <p>It is clear that the Soviets are playing hard to gain a dominant position in the
                    Near East area, and it is likely they have developed quite a hold on <persName
                        corresp="#p_NNNGA1">Nasser</persName>. This problem will probably remain
                    with us whatever may be the results of the talks in New York. I know that
                        <persName corresp="#p_FAB1">Foster</persName> is working closely with
                        <persName corresp="#p_LS1">Selwyn Lloyd</persName>, and I deeply deplore the
                    suggestions of the press both here and abroad that you and we are at cross
                    purposes.</p>
                <pb facs="0735" n="695" xml:id="pg_695"/>
                <p>With warm regard,</p>
                <p>As ever</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Ike E.</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>P.S. I got a chance, at this morning’s Press Conference,<note n="3"
                            xml:id="d328fn3">The transcript is printed in <hi rend="italic">Public
                                Papers of the Presidents of the United States: <persName
                                    corresp="#p_EDD1">Dwight D. Eisenhower</persName>, 1956</hi>,
                            pp. 880–894.</note> to say something on how much Britain &amp; the
                        British mean to us.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <persName>
                                <hi rend="strong">DE</hi>
                            </persName>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
